<subSubSection pageId="97" pageNumber="98" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="97.[151,1436,921,1090]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,956,981]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Description.</emphasis>
Lateral line undeveloped at this small size. Dorsal fin IV, 21; anal fin II, 13; vertebrae 11 + 17; anal-fin pterygiophores anterior to 1st haemal spine 3. 
<bibRefCitation author="Fourmanoir" box="[759,1008,993,1018]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" refString="Fourmanoir, P. (1976) Formes post-larvaires et juveniles de possons cotiers pris au chalut pelagique dans le Sud-ouest Pacifique. Extrait des Cahiers du Pacifique, 19, 47 - 88." type="journal article" year="1976">Fourmanoir (1976:54)</bibRefCitation>
erroneously recorded a count of X, 14 for the anal fin. This specimen has an enlarged, plate-like posttemporal and preopercle (
<figureCitation box="[1162,1246,1029,1054]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="32.[151,250,1392,1414]" captionTargetBox="[151,1405,193,1370]" captionTargetId="figure@32.[151,1436,193,1371]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURE 20. Heads of postflexion larval cepolids, A – B Acanthocepola Dana Sta. 3881, 9 mm SL (B cleared and stained); C, Owstonia, LACM 45967, 13.3 mm SL; D, Owstonia, USNM 307399, 13.2 mm SL, cleared and stained. Abbreviations: Pop = preopercle; Pt = posttemporal; Scl = supracleithrum; Soc = supraoccipital." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/165330/files/figure.png" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
D), like all other known postflexion 
<taxonomicName box="[367,474,1065,1088]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cepolidae" genus="Owstonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[367,474,1065,1088]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Owstonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
larvae.
</paragraph>
<caption box="[151,1403,1595,1617]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/256413/files/figure.png" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" targetBox="[236,1335,1170,1529]" targetPageId="97">
<paragraph blockId="97.[151,1403,1595,1617]" box="[151,1403,1595,1617]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,288,1595,1617]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">FIGURE 90.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[293,390,1595,1616]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cepolidae" genus="Owstonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[293,390,1595,1616]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Owstonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. 3, USNM 307399, 13.2 mm SL, Lifou Island. After Fourmanoir 1976, fig. 8. See also Fig. 20D.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="97.[151,1436,1661,1974]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,364,1661,1686]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Comparisons.</emphasis>
Meristic values of this larval specimen do not match any other species (see 
<tableCitation box="[1329,1423,1661,1686]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="9.[125,202,486,506]" captionTargetBox="[125,1815,581,1648]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="TABLE 2. Summary of selecteđ characters in species of Owstonia. 1" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/659FACF7BE3CAB780A2172FDFD50FE7F" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" tableUuid="659FACF7BE3CAB780A2172FDFD50FE7F">Table 2</tableCitation>
). Fourmanoir's (1976) illustration of the specimen is here reproduced as 
<figureCitation box="[984,1071,1697,1722]" captionStart="FIGURE 90" captionStartId="97.[151,250,1595,1617]" captionTargetBox="[236,1335,1170,1529]" captionTargetId="figure@97.[202,1385,1142,1573]" captionTargetPageId="97" captionText="FIGURE 90. Owstonia sp. 3, USNM 307399, 13.2 mm SL, Lifou Island. After Fourmanoir 1976, fig. 8. See also Fig. 20 D." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/256413/files/figure.png" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Fig. 90</figureCitation>
. He questionably identified the specimen as the Indian Ocean 
<taxonomicName authority="Smith" authorityName="Smith" box="[521,840,1733,1758]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cepolidae" genus="Owstonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="simotera">
<emphasis box="[521,739,1734,1757]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Owstonia simotera</emphasis>
(Smith)
</taxonomicName>
, presumably because it shares with that species a relatively large number of cheek scale rows; prior to clearing and staining the specimen we independently confirmed that it has 
<emphasis box="[389,471,1805,1829]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">at least</emphasis>
8 rows of cheek scales. Cheek scale row counts of 8 or more are known to occur only in two other species, 
<taxonomicName box="[388,624,1842,1866]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cepolidae" genus="Owstonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kamoharai">
<emphasis box="[388,624,1842,1866]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Owstonia kamoharai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[679,811,1842,1865]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cepolidae" genus="Owstonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="simotera">
<emphasis box="[679,811,1842,1865]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">O. simotera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In addition to the unlikely possibility of conspecificity given the known distributions (
<figureCitation box="[499,579,1877,1902]" captionStart="FIGURE 27" captionStartId="38.[151,250,1974,1996]" captionTargetBox="[203,1373,1135,1943]" captionTargetId="figure@38.[203,1384,1123,1952]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURE 27. Distributions of selected species of Owstonia based on specimens examined." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/256389/files/figure.png" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
) of 
<taxonomicName box="[624,756,1878,1901]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cepolidae" genus="Owstonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="simotera">
<emphasis box="[624,756,1878,1901]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">O. simotera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[810,965,1877,1901]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cepolidae" genus="Owstonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kamoharai">
<emphasis box="[810,965,1877,1901]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">O. kamoharai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the Lifou larva differs from both of these species in having more dorsal-fin spines IV (vs. III), anal-fin spines II (vs. I) and anal-fin pterygiophores anterior to 1st haemal spine 3 (vs. 2).
</paragraph>
